lence were almost exclusively young men whose attitudes and actions contrasted markedly with those of the earlier generation, who shared neither their juniors’ interest in creating sharply defined religious identities nor their propensity for violent conflict. Watts examines why the "final pagan generation"—born to the old ways and the old world in which it seemed to everyone that religious practices would continue as they had for the past two thousand years—proved both unable to anticipate the changes that imperially sponsored Christianity produced and unwilling to resist them. A compelling and provocative read, suitable for the general reader as well as students and scholars of the ancient world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aChristianity and other religionszRome. 0aPaganismzRome. 7aRELIGION / Ancient.2bisacsh  aancient history.  aancient rome.  aancient world.  achristian establishment.  achristianity.  aconversion.  aemperor constantine.  aemperors.  afinal pagan generation.  afourth century history.  ahistorical.  ahistory of christianity.  ahistory.  aimperial officers.  alater roman empire.  amediterranean history.  amobs.  apagan practices.  apagan sites.  apagan temples.  apolitical changes.  apolitics.  areligion.  areligious changes.  areligious identities.  areligious practices.  areligious studies.  areligious violence.  aroman empire.  aroman history.  arome.  aviolent conflict.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052028370140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095949140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520959491423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520959491/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of Califor